The decision to graduate in two years was practical: I had a sister who was also about to enter college, and I wanted to complete my degree earlier to ease my family's financial burden. Aware of the situation, I participated in research and other activities that were most uniquely available as a student. It helped me get into research and clubs early on, and in addition to my coursework, maximized the limited time I had. It forced me to identify opportunities quickly, build relationships with mentors, and seek out communities where I could learn from others. This experience shaped my approach to navigating challenges. 

Managing coursework while pursuing research, founding the Algorithms Club, and participating in competitive programming often required persistence. Working on various projects helped me grow quickly as a student and researcher. It focused my priorities and allowed me to go deeper into each one. One of the most valuable parts of my undergraduate study was meeting people with different academic backgrounds in research and running the club. For example, answering lines of questions while reading theory papers with younger students often helped us transition from minimum cuts and flows to more advanced topics like submodularity. These experiences showed me how different approaches to problems and reading papers led to better discussions and insights. In the Multimodal Interactions Lab, I also introduced new students to HCI literature and research tools, helping them explore the field.

In the Algorithms Club, I worked to make theoretical computer science accessible to students from computer science, mathematics, and other engineering disciplines. Working with people from different academic backgrounds and with different research interests often led to productive research discussions by challenging us to view the work through a different lens. As a graduate student, I'm eager to continue working with people across subdisciplines within theoretical computer science, to mentor students encountering new research areas, and to help create inclusive problem-solving communities. 
